s":["English (northern): habitational name from any of the places in Staffordshire, Yorkshire, and Northumberland, which are so called from Old English <i>fetherstān</i> ‘tetralith’, a prehistoric structure consisting of three upright stones capped with a headstone (from Old English <i>fe(o)ther-</i> ‘four’ + <i>stān</i> ‘stone’)."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":21,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When William Featherstonhaugh was born from 9 January 1360 to 8 January 1361, in Stanhope, Durham, England, United Kingdom, his father, William Featherstonhaugh, was 31 and his mother, Helena De Bostock of Kendal, was 32. He married Margaret Lancaster from 9 January 1384 to 8 January 1385, in England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1433, in Middlewich, Cheshir